The paper deals with the problem of guarding an orthogonal polygon, which is a classic problem in computational geometry and falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG). The algorithmic techniques used in the paper involve dynamic programming and geometric arguments, which are common in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also mentions approximation algorithms, which are studied in theoretical computer science (cs.CC) and game theory (cs.GT).
